[ two styles ]
this recipe can be steered toward two different results. each
decision point below is tagged with the style it favours:

  (A) OPEN/ARTISAN  - thick crackly crust, chewy centre,
                      big irregular air bubbles
  (B) EVEN/SPONGY   - thinner conventional crust, soft spongy
                      crumb, small evenly-distributed bubbles
                      (cafe sandwich-sourdough style)

the levers that separate them are: hydration, enrichment,
how hard you degas at shaping, and how you bake (dutch oven +
steam vs open / loaf tin). pick one column and stay in it.


[ starter maintenance ]
- 30g     / 18g filtered water
- 50g     / 30g flour
- 20-25g  / 12g starter


[ mixing ]
- combine in a bowl:
  - 500g bread flour
  - water:
    - (A) 350g (70%)  -- wetter dough lets bubbles balloon into big holes
    - (B) 310-325g (62-65%)  -- stiffer dough holds many small uniform cells
    - note: 70% assumes 80:20 white:wholemeal. for (B), nudging toward
      more wholemeal or some all-purpose softens gluten -> finer crumb
  - 50g active stiff starter (10%)
  - 10g salt
  - (B) enrichment -- the biggest lever for soft/spongy, also keeps it
    soft past day one. optional but recommended for the cafe texture:
    - ~20-30g oil or soft butter
    - swap 50-100g of the water above for milk
    - ~15g sugar or honey
  - (B) optional pinch of yeast -- for a faster, more uniform rise and
    reliably even bubbles (closest to typical cafe sandwich sourdough):
    - ~2-3g instant yeast
    - if used, fermentation will be much faster -- see timings below
- wait 30 mins
- do windowpane translucency test
  - if it tears, knead 2-3 mins, rest 10 mins, repeat


[ fermentation ]
- with wet hands, round the dough to make nice round surface
- cover bowl and let dough rise, go based on criteria not the clock:
  - 30% - 50% volume rise (use aliquot jar)
  - surface bubbles visible
  - jiggly texture when bowl shaken
  - sweet/sour smell
- timing:
  - sourdough only: 6-12 hrs
  - (B) + pinch of yeast: much faster, ~2-4 hrs -- watch the criteria,
    it will run away from you if you go by the old timings
- optionally stretch and fold during fermentation
  - (A) builds strength for big open holes
  - (B) skip or keep gentle -- you don't want a strong open structure


[ shaping ]
this is the other big lever between the two styles.

  (A) GENTLE -- preserve the gas you built:
      handle softly, don't press the air out.

  (B) DEGAS -- knock the air out for even crumb:
      press/flatten the dough out before folding, popping the big
      bubbles, then roll up tight with no trapped pockets. a tight
      gas-free roll is what gives the regular sponge.

- use batard (oval) or boulard (round)
- sprinkle some flour over dough while still in bowl
  - flip dough from bowl onto bench (i.e. topside in bowl -> bottomside on bench)
    - this is because topside in bowl is slightly drier
  - add some flour around edges of dough
  - (B) press the dough out flat here, knocking the big bubbles out
  - fold (sticky) now-topside over a few times, knocking excess flour off
    - right to middle
    - left to middle
    - top to middle
  - roll top to middle to yield a smooth topside
    - (B) roll firm and tight, no air gaps
  - add some flour on top
  - flip into banneton
  - (B) alt: loaf tin instead of banneton -- a tin bake (next section)
    is the easiest path to an even crumb + conventional sandwich crust


[ prooving ]
- cover and refrigerate 8-96 hours to proof, or proof at room temp for 1-3 hours
  - (B) + pinch of yeast: room-temp proof only, ~1-1.5 hrs, until puffy

baking -- this decides the crust:

  (A) DUTCH OVEN + STEAM -- thick crackly artisan crust:
    - set oven to 230°C with dutch oven inside and preheat for 30 mins
    - score & spritz loaf, optionally add rice flour
    - bake 30 mins with dutch oven lid on (trapped steam = thick crust)
    - bake until desired crust colour / until internal temp reaches 92°C
      (20 more mins) with lid off

  (B) OPEN BAKE -- thinner soft conventional crust:
    - set oven to 200-210°C (no dutch oven, no steam -- steam is what
      makes the thick crackly crust, so skip it here)
    - score the loaf
    - bake on a tray (or in the loaf tin) until golden / internal 92°C,
      ~40-45 mins total
    - immediately out of the oven, while still hot, brush the top with
      milk or melted butter for a soft, even, golden crust -- the
      residual heat lets it soak in and steams the crust soft
      (don't brush before/during the bake; that firms the crust)
